    "summary": {
      "background": "Deeper neural networks are more difficult to train due to the degradation problem, where accuracy saturates and then degrades rapidly with increasing depth, even when not caused by overfitting or vanishing gradients. This paper addresses this optimization difficulty by introducing a deep residual learning framework.",
      "contributions": [
        "Proposes residual learning framework that reformulates layers as learning residual functions with reference to layer inputs, making deeper networks easier to optimize.",
        "Demonstrates that residual networks (ResNets) can gain accuracy from considerably increased depth, achieving state-of-the-art results on ImageNet with up to 152 layers.",
        "Wins 1st place in ILSVRC 2015 classification, detection, localization, COCO detection, and COCO segmentation competitions.",
        "Provides comprehensive empirical evidence on ImageNet, CIFAR-10, and object detection tasks showing residual networks overcome the degradation problem."
      ],
      "methodology": "The core method introduces shortcut connections that perform identity mapping, adding the input of a stack of layers to its output, effectively learning residual functions F(x) = H(x) - x instead of the original mapping H(x). These identity shortcuts add no extra parameters or computational complexity and can be trained end-to-end with SGD and backpropagation.",
      "experiments": "Experiments are conducted on ImageNet 2012 classification (1.28M training images, 50k validation, 100k test), CIFAR-10 (50k training, 10k testing), and object detection on PASCAL VOC and MS COCO using Faster R-CNN. Baselines include plain networks of varying depths, VGG nets, GoogLeNet, and Highway networks.",
      "results": "ResNets with 152 layers achieve 3.57% top-5 error on ImageNet test set, outperforming all previous ensembles. On CIFAR-10, a 110-layer ResNet achieves 6.43% error, and a 1202-layer network trains successfully with <0.1% training error. On COCO detection, ResNet-101 provides a 28% relative improvement in mAP@[.5,.95] over VGG-16.",
      "limitations": "The 1202-layer ResNet on CIFAR-10 shows higher test error (7.93%) than the 110-layer network (6.43%) due to overfitting, as the model is unnecessarily large for the small dataset. The paper notes that combining with stronger regularization (e.g., maxout or dropout) may improve results but was not explored. Additionally, the optimization difficulties of deep plain nets are not fully explained and left for future study."
    },
